Introduction to Data Visualization with Seaborn¶

Introduction to Seaborn¶

  • Easy to use
  • Works well with pandas data structures
  • Built on top of matplotlib
In [ ]:
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
In [ ]:
height = [62, 64, 69, 75, 66, 68, 65, 71, 76, 73]
weight = [120, 136, 148, 175, 137, 165, 154, 172, 200, 187]

#!Notice that we have to specify x and y
sns.scatterplot(x=height, y=weight)
plt.figure(figsize=(4,3))
plt.show()

<Figure size 400x300 with 0 Axes>
In [ ]:
gender = ["Female", "Female", "Female", "Female",
           "Male", "Male", "Male", "Male", "Male", "Male"]

sns.countplot(x=gender)
plt.show()

Adding a third variable with hue¶

there is a special dataset tips which is included in seaborn by default

In [ ]:
tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")

hue_colors = {"Yes": "purple",
              "No": "orange"}

sns.scatterplot(x="total_bill", y="tip", data=tips,
                 hue="smoker", hue_order=["No", "Yes"],
                 palette = hue_colors)
plt.show()

Introduction to relational plots and subplots¶

Relational plots relplot:

  • lineplot
  • scatterplot

We use relplot cause it allows us to create subplots in a single figure

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            col="smoker" #could have used row
            )

plt.show()

If you have too many values (like several dayes of the week you can use col_wrap to wrap it into 2 lines instead of 1 and the usecol_order to specify the order)

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            col="day", #could have used row
            col_wrap=2,
            col_order=["Thur",
                       "Fri",
                       "Sat",
                       "Sun"])

plt.show()

Customizing scatter plots¶

size and hue

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            size="size",
            hue="size"
)

plt.show()

style

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            hue="smoker",
            style="smoker"
)

plt.show()

alpha

In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            alpha=0.4
)

plt.show()

Introduction to line plots¶

In [ ]:
mpg = pd.read_csv("databases/mpg.csv")

sns.relplot(x="model_year", y="mpg",
            data=mpg, kind="line") 
plt.show()
In [ ]:
sns.relplot(x="model_year", y="horsepower", 
            data=mpg,
            kind="line", 
            errorbar=None,
            style="origin", 
            hue="origin",
            markers=True,
            dashes=False)
plt.show()

Categorical plots (count plots, bar plots)¶

  • Involve a categorical variable (a couple of categories)
  • Comparisons between groups
  • we use catplot()
  • parameters col and row work the same way
In [ ]:
category_order = ["<2 hours", "2 to 5 hours", "5 to 10 hours", ">10 hours"]
survey = pd.read_csv("databases/student-alcohol-consumption.csv")
sns.catplot(x="study_time", 
            data=survey,
            kind="count",
            order = category_order)
plt.show()

The difference of bar plots is that they display mean of quantative variable per category and no the counts of it

In [ ]:
sns.catplot(x="day",
            y="total_bill",
            data=tips,
            kind="bar",
            errorbar=None,
            hue="day")

plt.show()

Box plots¶

  • shows the distribution of quantitative data
  • see the median, spread, skewness and outliers
  • facilitates comparisons between groups
In [ ]:
order = ["Dinner", "Lunch"]

g = sns.catplot(x="time",
                y="total_bill",
                data=tips,
                kind="box"
                ) #to ommit outliers
plt.show()

Point plots¶

  • show the mean of quantative variable
  • vertical lines show 95% confidence interals
  • x-axis is a categorical variable

We are using median instead of default mean to avoid outliers

In [ ]:
from numpy import median

sns.catplot(x="smoker",
              y="total_bill",
              data=tips,
              kind="point",
              estimator=median)

plt.show()

To avoid lines

In [ ]:
from numpy import median

sns.catplot(x="smoker",
              y="total_bill",
              data=tips,
              kind="point",
              linestyle="none",
              capsize=0.2,)

plt.show()

Changing plot style and color¶

Styles - sns.set_style:

  • "white" (the default one)
  • "dark"
  • "whitegrid"
  • "darkgrid"
  • "ticks"
In [ ]:
sns.set_style("darkgrid")

sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            size="size",
            hue="size"
)

plt.show()

Changing the pallete - sns.set_palette():

  • "RdBu"
  • "PRGn"
  • "RdBu_r"
  • "PRGn_r"

https://seaborn.pydata.org/tutorial/color_palettes.html

In [ ]:
sns.set_palette("RdBu")

category_order = ["<2 hours", "2 to 5 hours", "5 to 10 hours", ">10 hours"]
survey = pd.read_csv("databases/student-alcohol-consumption.csv")
sns.catplot(x="study_time", 
            data=survey,
            kind="count",
            order = category_order,
            hue="study_time")
plt.show()

Changing the scale of the plot - sns.set_context()

From smallest to largest:

  • "paper" (default value)
  • "notebook"
  • "talk"
  • "poster"
In [ ]:
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
sns.set_context("talk")

sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            size="size",
            hue="size"
)

plt.show()
sns.set_context("paper")

Adding titles and labels: Part 1¶

Object Type Plot Types Characteristics
FacetGrid relplot(), catplot() Can create subplots
AxesSubplot scatterplot(), countplot()... Only creates a single plot
In [ ]:
sns.set_style("darkgrid")
sns.set_context("talk")

g = sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            size="size",
            hue="size"
)

g.fig.suptitle("New Title", y=1.03)
plt.show()

Adding titles and labels: Part 2¶

In [ ]:
hue_colors = {"Yes": "purple",
              "No": "orange"}

g = sns.scatterplot(x="total_bill", y="tip", data=tips,
                 hue="smoker", hue_order=["No", "Yes"],
                 palette = hue_colors)

g.set_title("New Title", y=1.03)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.show()

Titles for subplots

In [ ]:
g = sns.relplot(x="total_bill",
            y="tip",
            data=tips,
            kind="scatter",
            col="smoker" #could have used row
            )
g.fig.suptitle("New Title", y=1.03)
g.set_titles("This is {col_name}")


#works with both FacetGrid and AxisSubplots
g.set(xlabel="New x label",
      ylabel="New y label")

plt.show()
